ion%3E%3C%2Ffigure%3E%3Cul%3E%3Cli%3EScientists%20have%20managed%20to%20extract%20evidence%20from%20an%20ancient%20fossil%20of%20early%20life%20on%20Earth.%C2%A0%3C%2Fli%3E%3Cli%3ERock%20in%20South%20Africa%20is%20thought%20to%20contain%20some%20of%20the%20oldest%20known%20fossils%20in%20the%20world.%3C%2Fli%3E%3Cli%3EStudying%20these%20samples%20can%20reveal%20clues%20about%20life%20on%20Earth%20over%203.4%20billion%20years%20ago.%3C%2Fli%3E%3C%2Ful%3E%3Cp%3EEarth%20may%20have%20been%20teeming%20with%20a%20complex%20ecosystem%20of%20microorganisms%20as%20far%20back%20as%203.4%20billion%20years%20ago.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EScientists%2C%20led%20by%20the%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.uni-goettingen.de%2Fen%2F125309.html%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3EUniversity%20of%20G%C3%B6ttingen%3C%2Fa%3E%20in%20Germany%2C%20studied%20fossils%20taken%20from%20the%20Buck%20Reef%20Chert%20in%20the%20Barberton%20Greenstone%20Belt%20in%20South%20Africa.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20area%20is%20known%20for%20having%20well-preserved%20ancient%20sedimentary%20rocks%20close%20to%20its%20surface%2C%20which%20can%20provide%20a%20snapshot%20of%20our%20planet's%20history.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EIn%20some%20of%20these%20rocks%2C%20researchers%20found%20chemical%20signatures%20that%20provided%20an%20insight%20into%20the%20biodiversity%20of%20ancient%20organisms%2C%20adding%20evidence%20to%20the%20early%20beginning%20of%20life%20on%20our%20planet.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BWhat%20I'm%20reading%20out%20of%20this%20is%20that%20early%20life%20was%20working%20very%20much%20similarly%20to%20life%20today%2C%26quot%3B%20Frances%20Westall%2C%20an%20expert%20in%20ancient%20biology%20from%20the%20French%20National%20Centre%20for%20Scientific%20Research%2C%20who%20was%20not%20involved%20in%20the%20study%2C%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.newscientist.com%2Farticle%2F2413292-traces-of-ancient-life-reveal-a-3-4-billion-year-old-ecosystem%2F%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Etold%20New%20Scientist%3C%2Fa%3E.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cfigure%3E%3Cimg%20width%3D%5C%222000%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22Three%20samples%20of%20fossils%20are%20shown%20side%20by%20side.%20The%20fossils%20are%20shown%20either%20in%20black%20and%20white%20or%20as%20seen%20under%20fluorescent%20light.%5C%22%20charset%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fi.insider.com%2F65ae5a2e617029e90a5ee610%3Fformat%3Djpeg%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%221000%5C%22%3E%3Cfigcaption%3ESide%20by%20side%20pictures%20show%20ancient%20fossils%20encased%20in%20rock%2C%20seen%20either%20under%20fluorescent%20light%20(left)%20or%20in%20Black%20and%20white%20(right.%20The%20fluorescence%20reveals%20chemical%20properties%20of%20the%20rock.%3Cp%3EM.%20Reinhardt%2C%20et%20al.%20Precambrian%20Research%202024%2C%20https%3A%2F%2Fdoi.org%2F10.1016%2Fj.precamres.2024.107289.%20CC-BY%2040.%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Ffigcaption%3E%3C%2Ffigure%3E%3Ch2%3ELife%20on%20Earth%20more%20than%203%20billion%20years%20ago%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cp%3EScientists%20think%20that%20life%20on%20Earth%20began%20around%204.3%20billion%20years%20ago%2C%20but%20tracking%20down%20evidence%20dating%20back%20to%20that%20time%20is%20a%20difficult%20task.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EStill%2C%20by%20drilling%20straight%20into%20ancient%20rock%2C%20scientists%20have%20found%20peculiar%2C%20carbon-rich%20layers%20in%20several%20cores%20taken%20from%20around%20the%20world.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThese%20layers%20are%20widely%20thought%20to%20be%20fossilized%20life%2C%20frozen%20in%20rock%20billions%20of%20years%20ago.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20oldest%20accepted%20rock%20core%20containing%20fossilized%20life%20was%20found%20in%20Pilbara%2C%20Australia.%20This%20is%20thought%20to%20be%20more%20than%203.5%20million%20years%20old.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EOlder%20carbon-rich%20layers%20have%20been%20uncovered%2C%20but%20because%20of%20their%20age%2C%20it's%20not%20possible%20to%20know%20for%20sure%20that%20these%20are%20fossils%20or%20another%20non-biological%20process.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3ESo%20scientists%20have%20been%20racing%20to%20understand%20all%20they%20can%20from%20these%20ancient%20fossils.%20And%20what%20they've%20found%20is%20that%20Earth%20was%20already%20teaming%20with%20life%20more%20than%20three%20billion%20years%20ago.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BIt's%20very%20difficult%20to%20see%20the%20trend%2C%20simply%20because%20of%20a%20lack%20of%20well-preserved%20rocks%2C%26quot%3B%20says%20Westall.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BPersonally%2C%20I%20think%20life%20emerged%20on%20Earth%20during%20the%20Hadean%2C%20probably%20about%204.2%2C%204.1%20billion%20years%20%5Bago%5D%2C%26quot%3B%20Westall%20said%20referring%20to%20a%20period%20of%20time%20that%20ended%20about%20four%20billion%20years%20ago.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch2%3EMicrobes'%20metabolisms%2C%20billions%20of%20years%20after%20they%20died%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20samples%20from%20the%20Barberton%20Greenstone%20Belt%20are%20among%20the%20oldest%20known%20fossils%20of%20life%20%E2%80%94%20dating%20back%20to%20about%203.42%20billion%20years%20ago.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cfigure%3E%3Cimg%20width%3D%5C%221466%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22a%20map%20pinpoints%20the%20location%20where%20the%20rock%20cores%20were%20extracted%5C%22%20charset%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fi.insider.com%2F65ae584a43bb77284b9f10e7%3Fformat%3Djpeg%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%221062%5C%22%3E%3Cfigcaption%3EA%20map%20shows%20where%20the%203.4%20billion%20year%20old%20fossils%20were%20extracted.%3Cp%3EGoogle%20Maps.%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Ffigcaption%3E%3C%2Ffigure%3E%3Cp%3EEarlier%20analyses%20had%20looked%20at%20the%20shape%20of%20the%20fossilized%20microbes%20in%20the%20rock%2C%20suggesting%20these%20were%20varied%20and%20probably%20lived%20near%20water.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20new%20analysis%2C%20published%20in%20the%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.sciencedirect.com%2Fscience%2Farticle%2Fpii%2FS0301926824000020%23da005%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Epeer-reviewed%20journal%20%3C%2Fa%3EPrecambrian%20Research%20on%20January%2012%2C%20pushed%20the%20analysis%20even%20further%20by%20looking%20at%20the%20chemicals%20that%20made%20up%20the%20microbes.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3ETheir%20study%20showed%20that%2C%20as%20expected%2C%20there%20were%20a%20lot%20of%20%26quot%3Bphotoautotrophs%26quot%3B%20back%20then%2C%20meaning%20the%20bacteria%20were%20able%20to%20take%20sunlight%20and%20turn%20it%20into%20energy%2C%20much%20like%20some%20bacteria%20that%20exist%20today.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EBut%20they%20also%20found%20evidence%20that%20some%20microbes%20were%20likely%20already%20able%20to%20use%20up%20sulfate%20and%20make%20complex%20chemicals%20like%20methane%20and%20acetate.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThis%20reinforces%20the%20idea%20that%20life%20was%20already%20very%20complex%203.4%20billion%20years%20ago%2C%20capable%20of%20using%20up%20carbon%20in%20a%20variety%20of%20ways%20that%20we%20still%20see%20today%2C%20the%20scientists%20said%20in%20the%20study.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BThese%20results%20highlight%20the%20existence%20of%20an%20advanced%20biological%20carbon%20cycle%20as%20early%20as%203.42%20Ga%20ago%2C%26quot%3B%20they%20said.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cdiv%3ERead%20the%20original%20article%20on%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fremnants-life-in-rocks-rich-ecosystem-3-billion-years-ago-2024-1%5C%22%3EBusiness%20Insider%3C%2Fa%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%22%2C%22published%22%3A1705927517000%2C%22visual%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fi.insider.com%2F65ae5a47617029e90a5ee61a%3Fformat%3Djpeg%22%2C%22originID%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fremnants-life-in-rocks-rich-ecosystem-3-billion-years-ago-2024-1%22%2C%22summary%22%3A%22Researchers%20found%20chemical%20signatures%20in%20rocks%20that%20provided%20an%20unprecedented%20insight%20into%20the%20biodiversity%20of%20ancient%20organisms.%22%2C%22author%22%3A%22mguenot%40businessinsider.com%20(Marianne%20Guenot)%22%2C%22engagement%22%3A40%2C%22canonicalUrl%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fremnants-life-in-rocks-rich-ecosystem-3-billion-years-ago-2024-1%22%2C%22cdnAmpUrl%22%3A%22%22%2C%22ampUrl%22%3A%22%22%7